    "story_body": "<h2>The Story of Octile</h2><p>In 250 BC, Archimedes carved a square into 14 ivory pieces and  posed a simple question to the world: <em>How many ways can you put them back together?</em></p><p>That question challenged humanity for over two thousand years. The answer — <strong>536</strong> — wasn't discovered until 2003, with the help of computers.</p><h3>From 14 Pieces to 11</h3><p>Octile carries that same spirit onto an 8&times;8 board. Eleven tiles, Sixty‑four cells, One goal: fill every square. Three grey tiles are already placed. The rest is up to you.</p><p>We asked ourselves: <em>how many puzzles could this create?</em> The answer: <strong>over 90,000</strong> — and every single one has a solution.</p><h3>Why &ldquo;Octile&rdquo;?</h3><p><strong>Oct</strong> (eight) for the 8&times;8 board. <strong>Tile</strong> for the joy of fitting pieces together. That’s it.</p><p><em>Archimedes had ivory. You have pixels. The fun hasn't changed.</em></p>",
    "taglines": [
      "<strong>91,024 puzzles.</strong> One board. Your move.",
      "Simple rules. Endless satisfaction.",
      "<strong>An ancient puzzle, reimagined.</strong> Now at your fingertips.",
      "Think slowly. Place precisely.",
      "Fill the board. Feel the perfect fit.",
      "Every piece has its place."
    ],
    "win_facts": [
      "In 250 BC, Archimedes created a puzzle like this using ivory. You’re continuing a tradition over 2,000 years old.",
      "\"Stomachion\" may come from the Greek word for \"stomach\" — because puzzles like this are equal parts painful and delightful.",
      "The smallest tile covers 1 cell. The largest covers 10. Together, they fill the board perfectly.",
      "Three gray tiles are already fixed. The remaining eight are yours to arrange. No rush.",
      "Archimedes had ivory. You have pixels. The satisfaction of a perfect fit hasn’t changed.",
      "Every Octile puzzle has a solution. If you’re stuck, it’s not the puzzle — it’s the perspective.",
      "Before giving up, try rotating that piece. Sometimes one turn is all it takes.",
      "The eight colored tiles come in four colors — red, white, blue, and yellow. Probably not by accident.",
      "Your brain is solving a constraint satisfaction problem right now. It sounds technical. It feels great.",
      "Some players finish in under 15 seconds. A hint: start with the corners."
    ],
    "motivation_quotes": [
      "Every puzzle has a solution. Take your time.",
      "Stuck? Try placing a piece from a different angle.",
      "The answer might be in the piece you haven’t rotated yet.",
      "Archimedes didn’t rush either. Neither should you.",
      "The Hint button can reveal where one piece belongs — if you need it."
    ],
